    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Cellphone Lifeline</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Carol S Cantrell letter on importance of having her children carry cellphones to school so they can be reached in emergency</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''School Cellphone Bans Topple (You Can't Suspend Everyone)'' (front page, Sept. 29):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''School Cellphone Bans Topple (You Can't Suspend Everyone)'' (front page, Sept. 29):</p>
        <p>When both of my children were in New York City public high schools in 2001, I was wholeheartedly against their owning cellphones. My son was a senior at the High School of Economics and Finance, a block south of the World Trade Center.</p>
        <p>Because we had no way to reach each other, I did not know that he was alive until the afternoon of Sept. 11, 2001.</p>
        <p>The next Saturday, both children and I went to a phone store and bought phones.</p>
        <p>From that day on, it has been of utmost importance to me to know that I can call my kids and find out where they are and, most important, to know that they are all right.</p>
        <p>Carol S. Cantrell  Staten Island, Sept. 29, 2004</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
